question:
Find the rank of the matrix  $\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
-1  & z & 2 \\ 
1 & -1 & 1\\
z  & -1 & 1\end{array}
\right)$, where $z$ is a real number.

The spectral radius of the matrix  $A = \begin{bmatrix}
-3 &  1 \\
1 & -3 \end{bmatrix}$ is:

Suppose that $A=\left( 
 \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 1 & 3 \\ 
0 & 0 & 5  \\ 
-1 & -2 & 1  \\ 
3 & 1 & 2 \end{array} \right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 1 & 0 \\ 
2 & 1 & 1 \\ 
1 & 1 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $C=\left(  \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 2 & 0  \\ 
2 & 4 & 1  \\ 
3 & 6 & 2  \\ 
-4 & -8 & 1  \end{array}
\right)$.

Which matrix has the rank $2$ ?

Find $a$ such that the matrix $\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 2 & 3 \\ 
4 & 5 & 6 \\ 
3 & 2 & a \end{array}
\right)$ is singular.

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 3 & 2 \\ 
1 & 0 & 3 \\ 
0 & -1 & -1 \end{array}
\right)$ and $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 0 & 0 \\ 
2 & 1 & 1 \\ 
-1 & 1 & -1 \end{array}
\right)$. Find $\mathrm{det} \left(X\right)$ knowing that $$\frac{1}{2} X\cdot A +  \mathrm{det} \left(B\right) \cdot A=B$$

Which of the following vectors is an eigenvector of the matrix $A = \begin{bmatrix}
-3 & 1 \\
1 & -3 \end{bmatrix}$?

Find ${\left(C^T \cdot B-6 \cdot I^{-1}\right)}^2$, where $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 0 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$, $C=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
3 & 3 & 1 \\ 
1 & -2 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, and $I$  -- identity matrix.

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 0 & -1 \\ 
3 & 1 & 0 \\ 
-2 & 1 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find matrix $B$ such that matrices $A$ and $B$ are inverses.

Let $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 2 \\ 
3 & 4 \end{array}
\right)$ and $B=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
0 & 2 \\ 
3 & k \end{array}
\right)$.

For what value of $k$ the matrices $A$ and $B$ will be commuting?

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
-2  & -1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 1 & 2\\
2  & 1 & -2\end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
4  & 1 & 0\end{array}
\right)$, and $C=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
0  & 3 & -1\end{array}
\right)$. Find $X$ if $X\cdot A-B=C$.

Consider $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$ and  $B=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
a & b \\ 
c & d \end{array}
\right)$. If $A$ commutes with $B$, (AB = BA) then which of the following statements is correct?

Find the real values of $m$ for which the following set of vectors $V=\left( \begin{array}{r}  
1\\ 
2 \\
m \end{array}
\right)$, $Z=\left( \begin{array}{r}  
1\\ 
-1 \\
m \end{array}
\right)$, and
$W=\left( \begin{array}{r}  
3\\ 
m+2 \\
1 \end{array}
\right)$ is linearly independent.

Let $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 2 & 0 \\ 
2 & -4 & 0 \end{array}
\right)$. Which of the following statements is correct?

